2199E - Supersequence
Let's try to understand what the array $$$b$$$ might look like. To construct the shortest array in which $$$a$$$ appears as a subsequence, we can use the following process:
set $$$b_1 = a_1$$$;
add as few elements as possible so that the next one can be $$$a_2$$$. If $$$a_1  \lt  a_2$$$, then each subsequent element should be greater than the previous one by $$$1$$$. If $$$a_1  \gt  a_2$$$, then each subsequent element should be less than the previous one by $$$1$$$. If $$$a_1 = a_2$$$, we can place either $$$a_1 + 1$$$ or $$$a_1 - 1$$$ between them;
similarly go from $$$a_2$$$ to $$$a_3$$$;
and so on.
Thus, the number of elements that will be between the occurrences of $$$a_i$$$ and $$$a_{i+1}$$$ in the array $$$b$$$ can be easily determined: if they are equal, then there is $$$1$$$ element between them; otherwise, there are $$$|a_i - a_{i+1}| - 1$$$ elements between them. This allows us to determine the position of each element $$$a_i$$$ in the array $$$b$$$.
Consider the elements between the occurrences of $$$a_i$$$ and $$$a_{i+1}$$$. If these two numbers are equal, we cannot uniquely determine the element between them — it could be either $$$a_i + 1$$$ or $$$a_i - 1$$$. However, if they are different, all elements between them are uniquely determined, and knowing $$$a_i$$$, $$$a_{i+1}$$$, and the index of the element in the block between them makes it easy to reconstruct the element itself.
Thus, to answer each query, we need to know which block the element at position $$$x_i$$$ belongs to (or, possibly, whether it is an occurrence of one of the elements in the array $$$a$$$). If we list the starting positions of each block in the array, we can determine which block $$$x_i$$$ belongs to using binary search. This gives us a solution in $$$O(n + q \log n)$$$.
